h claimed power, engaging sometimes as rivals and sometimes as allies. Maier focuses on recurring institutional constellations: project-states including both democracies and dictatorships that sought not just to retain power but to transform their societies; new forms of imperial domination; global networks of finance; and the international associations, foundations, and NGOs that tried to shape public life through allegedly apolitical appeals to science and ethics.In this account, which draws on the author’s studies over half a century, Maier invites a rethinking of the long twentieth century. His history of state entanglements with capital, the decline of public projects, and the fragility of governance explains the fraying of our own civic culture—but also allows hope for its recovery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical sociology. 0aPolitics and culturexHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and culturexHistoryy21st century. 0aPolitics and culture-History-20th century. 0aPolitics and culture-History-21st century. 0aPolitics, PracticalxSocial aspects. 0aPolitics, Practical-Social aspects. 0aTwentieth century. 0aTwenty-first century. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh  aOPEC.  acapitalism.  achina.  acoal.  acommunism.  acountervailing.  adebt.  aemployment.  afascism.  afrance.  agermany.  ainflation.  aitaly.  ajapan.  alabor.  amarshall plan.  aoil.  aparties.  apostwar order.  aresource empire.  asocial democracy.  asteel.  atotalitarianism.  atrade unions.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz9783111319